eCompiler to compile fixtures and directly set the processor, which avoids the need for discovery. However, I’m thinking about creating source files for the processor and compiling them, which poses challenges in native images since `javac` might not be available. So, I may need to rely on the test's own processor class instead.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Java test structure**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the one-to-one mapping and whether \\\"keeping coverage for the active class in its own dedicated Java test file\\\" really means no auxiliary files should be necessary. Maybe having a nested public static class is acceptable if the service provider supports it. I wonder if the ServiceLoader provider class can also be nested as public static? It seems to load binary names with $, which raises some questions about the service file structure.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_bhyYP9OgIV1UNqHL6NASoIpR|fc_0a92bb1da5926a480169f0e8540f7481939d5709efa147ec89", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg -n \"-processor|XprintProcessorInfo|ServiceLoader|ANNOTATION_PROCESSOR_PATH|setProcessors\" local_repositories/source_context/org.eclipse.jdt/ecj/3.26.0/main/extracted tests/src/org.eclipse.jdt/ecj/3.26.0/src/test/java -S", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 775, "output": 1316, "cacheRead": 14336, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 16427, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777395775183, "responseId": "resp_0a92bb1da5926a480169f0e83f923c8193966c608aa9c44768"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_bhyYP9OgIV1UNqHL6NASoIpR|fc_0a92bb1da5926a480169f0e8540f7481939d5709efa147ec89", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "(no output)\n\nCommand exited with code 1"}], "details": {}, "isError": true, "timestamp": 1777395796537}]}
